Data exploration

Univariate Analysis

Fixed acidity

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.800   6.300   6.800   6.855   7.300  14.200

Most wines have a fixed acidity between 5.5 \(g / dm^3\) and 8 \(g / dm^3\)

Volatile acidity

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0800  0.2100  0.2600  0.2782  0.3200  1.1000

In this case, the volatile acidity of most of the wines is between 0.15 \(g / dm^3\) and 0.35 \(g / dm^3\)

Citric avid

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0000  0.2700  0.3200  0.3342  0.3900  1.6600

The citric acid content of most of the wines is between 0.2 \(g / dm^3\) and 0.45 \(g / dm^3\)

Residual sugar

Better change the scale to have a clearer view of it:

It looks like the residual sugar is a bimodal distribution with modes around 1.5 \(g / dm^3\) and 8 \(g / dm^3\)

Chlorides

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.00900 0.03600 0.04300 0.04577 0.05000 0.34600

Looks like I need to zoom in to get any valuable info:

Its curious, there are bins with 0 wines count on it approximately every 0.008 \(g / dm^3\). This is probably because the tools used to measure it, maybe they changed the scale at that point and that's why there are those empty places on the plot (a wine belonging to that place will be placed on one of the sides due to tools measurement error).

Free sulfur dioxide

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.00   23.00   34.00   35.31   46.00  289.00

Again, looks like the free sulfur dioxide content of most of the wines is somewhere between 15 \(g / dm^3\) and 30 \(g / dm^3\)

Total sulfur dioxide

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.00   23.00   34.00   35.31   46.00  289.00

As expected the total sulfur dioxide content of the wines if higher than the free sulfur dioxide, and most of the wines are between 70 \(g / dm^3\) and 200 \(g / dm^3\)

Density

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9871  0.9917  0.9937  0.9940  0.9961  1.0390

The density of the wines is very concentrated around 0.99 \(g/cm^3\) and 1 \(g/cm^3\), so it is practically the same density as the water. It would be interesting to check how the alcohol content is related to this on the multivariate analysis part.

pH

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

Most of the wines have a pH between 3 and 3.5. Because of this, wines are considered acid substances (and acid has a pH lower than 7)

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

Bivariate analysis

Now I will draw a matrix with GGally to have an overview on how each variable is related to the other. I will drop the column X because it is just a count of the rows.

At a glance, it looks like there is a strong correlation between residual sugar and density and density is also correlated to alcohol, as we should expect.

It's curious that there is also a relation between quality and chlorides, the wines with low density of chlorides are either very good or very bad. while the wines with a high density are average quality wines.

There is a similar relation between the pH of the wine and his quality, looks like the better the wine, the closer its pH to 3.3, but looking at the pH histogram, that's maybe because most of the wines on the dataset are close to that pH value.

Acidity

There are 3 variables that measure acidity of the wines: fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity and citric.acid. I will check how they are related to the pH on the next graph:

It seems like there is only a weak relation between fixed.acidity and pH, the other variables doesn't show any pattern here. It is logical because there is a bigger amount of this acid than the other two.

It is also curious that there are a lot of wines with fixed amounts of citric acid at 0.5 \(g/dm^3\) and 0.75 \(g/dm^3\) and looks like there is some at 0.3 \(g/dm^3\) too, I will zoom in the plot to check it out:

No, it doesn't look that there is something at 0.3 \(g/dm^3\), however the clear lines at 0.5 and 0.75 \(g/dm^3\) makes me think that citric acid is artificially added to some wines, maybe to add 'freshness' to it as the metadata says.

Sulfur Dioxide

Let's check if wine quality has any relation with the sulfur dioxide content. Looking at the bottom of the plot, is looks like a lot of bad quality wines have a low proportion of free sulfur dioxide.

Doesn't looks like there is any relation on this plots.

Let's check the relation between density of the wine and its alcohol content, trimming out some outliers:

Final Plots and Summary

1. Residual sugar and density

First I'm going to plot the residual sugar against the density of the wine, coloring the point by the alcohol content.

This plot clearly shows how the sugar content and the alcohol affects the density of the wine. Wines with high alcohol and low sugar content shows lower densities than wines with low alcohol and high sugar content.

Numerically they show a correlation of:

## [1] 0.8389665

When I divide the plots by wine quality on the lower plot, it shows that the high quality wines have usually less density than the rest because a high level of alcohol and low level of residual sugar.

This also look clear when I calculate the summary of the density for each wine quality (in order: high, medium, low):

2. Ph and chlorides

As I saw before, wine quality is also related to the chlorides content and pH. I will draw a boxplot to clarify this relation.

This plot clearly shows the interesting fact that almost all of the wines rated 9 points in quality have a low chlorides content and a high pH factor.

This makes me think that pH and chlorides is very important for a wine, so the less acid it is, the better.

Checking it numerically, this is the summary for the wines pH, from better to worse:

3. Heatmap of wine variables

To wrap up, I will draw a heatmap comparing all the variables of the wines separating them by wine quality.

Here I can see how the High Quality Wines have usually more alcohol than the rest, also, the density of the wines rated Low Quality Wines is higher than the others, and we can see that a lot of High Quality Wines have very small levels of residual sugar. This is probably related to the alcohol content, because the ferment process turn sugar into alcohol.

Reflections

The goal of this project was to check which variables affected the wine quality.

On the first part of it. I just plotted all the variables alone and combined with others to have a general idea of how they related to each other. I found that many of them have no relation at all, but a few ones did have, like the wine quality and the chlorides content or the alcohol content, and the residual sugar and alcohol content with the density of the wine.

I found some strange holes on the chlorides and sulphates histograms that I attribute to the tools used to measure the values. It would be great to have some information about those tools and see if we can get more precise measurements in the future. Anyways, I think that measurement errors do not affect much to the project results.

Even when most of the variables doesn't looks clearly related to wine quality, from the plots from above, it looks clear that most of the high quality wines have a alcohol level above the average and a residual sugar content below the average of the dataset. This two things combines makes good quality wines usually less dense than the rest, this can be taken as a rule of thumb to distinguish between good and bad wines.

Also the chlorides content and pH looks important and good wines usually have a low content of chlorides and high value of pH (they are less acid than the rest)

The values measured on this dataset are only a few of all the chemical components a wine has (info), so it would be great to enlarge this dataset with more measurements of other components to see if we can get a clearer picture on how to identify good wines from bad ones.

Also, on the dataset metadata explains that the quality variable is the median of the 3 evaluations made by wine experts. I think it would be useful here to also the mean of this evaluations, and run the analysis with it instead of the median.
